06043nam a22009255i 9783110681413DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020942054  a97831106814137 a10.1515/97831106814132doi  a(DE-B1597)537624  a(OCoLC)1197550919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aJC153.H52bB7413 202004a320.12231 aBredekamp, Horst, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeviathan :bBody politic as visual strategy in the work of Thomas Hobbes /cHorst Bredekamp. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (293 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- t1. Hobbes, his Leviathan, its frontispiece -- t2. The authorship of the Leviathan frontispiece -- t3. The “Artificiall Man” -- t4. Qualities and appearances -- t5. “Mastering” time -- t6. Endurance: the “Common-Wealth” as bulwark, constraint, aspiration -- tAppendix I: Excerpts from Leviathan -- tAppendix II: Images and Portraits -- tAppendix III0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHorst Bredekamp’s subject is the astute deployment and perennial resonance of the startling image of the body politic that dominates the frontispiece to Leviathan: a treatise on the psychology of the individual and the dynamic of the multitude, published in 1651 by the English philosopher Thomas Hobbes. Affirming the centrality of such a figural device for this pioneering theorist of the state, Bredekamp goes on to address the art-historical dimension of the mesmerising etched title-page. In his central chapters he explores the extraordinary range of sources – from socio-cultural tradition to scientific advances – on which the author and his artist-collaborator may have drawn. In conclusion, he reveals Hobbes to be no less passionate than shrewd in his belief that the constraints and amenities of a tolerable life in common attest to the potency of the visual. As appendices, two essays and catalogues explore the portraits made of Hobbes as well as illustrations that appeared in his other works, thus systematically completing the exploration of the images connected with this exceptional philosopher.  aVon Natur aus ist der Mensch so frei wie wölfisch. Um sich selbst zu bändigen, muss er folglich einen künstlichen Riesen schaffen: den Staat, der als übergeordnete Instanz den permanenten Bürgerkrieg zu unterdrücken und Frieden zu schaffen vermag. Diese Essenz von Thomas Hobbes' "Leviathan" ist bis heute ebenso vehement verworfen wie bekräftigt worden. Zu den Mitteln, mit denen der Leviathan die Menschen vom Unfrieden abhält, gehören Bilder, und aus diesem Grund steht dem Leviathan ein Frontispiz voran. Das Buch erschließt mit Abraham Bosse den Künstler des Frontispizes, stellt sämtliche Varianten dieses Urbildes des modernen Staates zusammen und versucht, die Vorgeschichte seiner politischen Ikonographie zu klären.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical sciencevEarly works to 1800. 0aState, ThevEarly works to 1800. 4aBildwissenschaft. 4aStaatstheorie. 4aThomas Hobbes.  aThomas Hobbes.  atheory of state.  avisual culture.1 aClegg, Elizabeth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2020z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:d